    <p> When I was upright in the morning there wasn't much to remember from the 130km/h storm we had at night. Since I had a place with a power connection, the heating ran overnight and I didn't notice the clinking cold that must have been hung up at night. Not much of all of this was to be remembered. It was sunny and pleasant to be outside. Only the mountains that surrounded me had bought snow and shifted the snow border down by a few meters. </p>
    <p> The morning I wetted on the Internet and with phone calls to my loved ones. The whole thing with a wonderful view over Mount Cook with approx. 3700 meters and its surrounding 2000s. I was shortly before that one night in the area, but I wanted to look at more from New Zealand. So I started in the afternoon to look at the Tasman Glacier. It was really impressive with its huge glacier lake. It is quite easy to see that a glacier extends over time and also defrosts again. I had to climb onto a stately hill and then get a fantastic view of the lake and glacier at the top. I found the sight much better and more impressive than that of Franz Josef or Fox Glacier, both of which are advertised extra. I only found out that the three glaciers around Mount Cook at all exist because I had sat down on a topographical card and checked what existed around Mount Cook. I also can't remember that I would have found a sign for the glaciers on the streets. </p>
    <p> I would also have liked to see the other two glaciers, which also push down on Mount Cook, but I wanted to drive to the east coast. So I slowly decided to make my way to Oamaru. </p>
