    <p> The route there was quite easy to drive. Once in the village, I drove directly to the penguine colony described in the travel guide. There I had to find that a tourist center was built around the colony, which also has quite expensive admission prices. I decided not to pay the price, got a pizza cheaply and drove to the parking lot for the night. </p>
    <p> The next morning, the first thing I drove to the Moeraki Boulders. A group of large stones that are in the surf and were sucked in the weather. It was nice to look at but as so often, a group of running Asians arrived with me, who were pushing around the best motif. I then drove back to Oamaru for the tourist information and found that there is a second penguin colony in the village. So I drove there. The beach and the cliffs are called Buschy Beach. There you could sift pingunine even in the afternoon. What I enjoyed again before I drove to the next night camp. </p>
    <p> When I arrived in Dorie in the night camp, it was a little creepy there. No light. Everything surrounded by high bushes. Somehow it looked like a ghost village. The morning after that, the whole thing looked a good bit friendlier. The campsite was located directly on a very nice and very lonely beach. After enjoying this sight for some time, I went on my last stage to Chistchurch where I spent the rest of the day cleaning the car and packing my things together again. Of course, everything is very leisurely. </p>
    <p> What I did in Christchurch then I will tell you next time. </p>
